y the livingspirit, proposed a permeable, legible boundary between the living and the dead. This inaugurated a revolution in European aesthetics, implanting the germ of an extraordinarily productive narrative idea that enriched Romantic literature for decades. Poets and novelists created a large cast of characters who crossed the boundary between death and life with the help of some form of reading: figures like Keats's Glaucus, Kleist's Elizabeth Kohlhaas, Shelley'sFrankenstein (and the monster he creates), Maturin's Melmoth, Poe's Madeline Usher, and Gautier's Spirite. Clayton Koelb demonstrates that such fictions offer a nuanced consideration of the most urgent question facing any theoryof life: how do material bodies come to acquire, to lose, and then perhaps to regain the immaterial intellectual/spiritual quality that defines animate beings? Clayton Koelb is Guy B. Johnson Professor of German, English, and Comparative Literature and Chair of the Department of Germanic Languages and Literatures at the University of North Carolina, Chapel Hill.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aLiteraturexHistory and criticismxTheory, etc. 0aRomanticism. 4aEnglish & American Literature. 4aGerman Literature. 4aModern Literature. 4aPhilosophy. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / European / German.2bisacsh  aAnimate Beings.  aEuropean Romanticism.  aLiterature and Philosophy.  aReading.  aRomantic Literature.  aTheory of Life.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertBoydell and Brewer Complete eBook-Package pre 2013z978311143139040uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978157113804040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781571138040423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781571138040/original  a978-3-11-143139-0  Boydell and Brewer Complete eBook-Package pre 2013b2013  aGBV-deGruyter-alles